---
import CalculatorLayout from '../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro';
import NetWorthCalculator from '../components/calculators/NetWorthCalculator';
import { TAX_YEAR } from '../lib/constants';

const title = `Net Worth Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}: Track Your Total Wealth`;
const description = `Calculate your net worth for ${TAX_YEAR} by adding up all assets and subtracting liabilities. See how you compare to others in your age group and track progress.`;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How do I calculate my net worth?',
    answer: `Net worth = Total Assets − Total Liabilities. Assets include: cash and savings, investment accounts (401k, IRA, brokerage), real estate equity, vehicle value, and other property. Liabilities include: mortgage balance, student loans, auto loans, credit card debt, and any other debts. A positive net worth means you own more than you owe.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the average net worth by age in the US?',
    answer: `According to the Federal Reserve's Survey of Consumer Finances, median net worth by age group is approximately: Under 35: $39,000; 35-44: $135,600; 45-54: $247,200; 55-64: $364,500; 65-74: $409,900; 75+: $335,600. Mean (average) net worth is much higher due to wealthy outliers — the median is a better benchmark for most people.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I include my home in my net worth?',
    answer: `Yes, your home equity (market value minus mortgage balance) should be included in your net worth calculation. However, it's useful to track both total net worth and "investable net worth" (excluding home equity) since your home isn't a liquid asset. If your home represents more than 50% of your net worth, you may want to diversify.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'How can I increase my net worth?',
    answer: `The three ways to grow net worth: (1) Increase the gap between income and spending — save more by cutting expenses or earning more; (2) Pay down high-interest debt (credit cards first, then other debts); (3) Invest consistently — maximize 401(k) match, contribute to IRA, and invest in low-cost index funds. Time and compound growth do the heavy lifting.`,
  },
];

const relatedCalculators = [
  { title: 'Savings Calculator', href: '/savings-calculator/', desc: 'Reach your savings goals' },
  { title: '401(k) Calculator', href: '/401k-calculator/', desc: 'Retirement savings growth' },
  { title: 'Compound Interest', href: '/compound-interest-calculator/', desc: 'Investment growth over time' },
  { title: 'Debt Payoff', href: '/credit-card-payoff-calculator/', desc: 'Eliminate debt faster' },
  { title: 'Paycheck Calculator', href: '/', desc: 'Maximize take-home pay' },
];

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'WebApplication',
  name: `Net Worth Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}`,
  description,
  url: 'https://truetakehomepay.com/net-worth-calculator/',
  applicationCategory: 'FinanceApplication',
  operatingSystem: 'Any',
  offers: { '@type': 'Offer', price: '0', priceCurrency: 'USD' },
  inLanguage: 'en-US',
};
---

<CalculatorLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  h1={`Net Worth Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}`}
  intro={`Calculate your total net worth by listing all your assets and liabilities. See how you compare to others in your age group and track your financial progress over time.`}
  faqs={faqs}
  relatedCalculators={relatedCalculators}
  schema={schema}
  sources={`Federal Reserve Survey of Consumer Finances (SCF), Bureau of Labor Statistics, Federal Reserve Economic Data (FRED). Last updated for ${TAX_YEAR}.`}
>
  <NetWorthCalculator client:idle />

  <Fragment slot="content">
    <section class="border-t border-slate-200 px-4 py-16 dark:border-slate-800 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose prose-slate dark:prose-invert mx-auto max-w-3xl">
        <h2 id="what-net-worth-tells-you">What Net Worth Really Tells You About Your Finances</h2>
        <p>Net worth is the simplest and most honest snapshot of your financial health. It is the total value of everything you own minus everything you owe, distilled into a single number. Unlike income, which tells you how much money flows through your hands, net worth tells you how much actually stays. Unlike your bank balance, which fluctuates with every paycheck and every bill, net worth captures the full scope of your financial position including retirement accounts, home equity, investments, and all forms of debt. When a financial planner sits down with a new client, the first thing they want to know is not the client's salary or credit score. It is their net worth, because that number reveals more about their true financial standing than any other single metric.</p>
        <p>A positive net worth means you own more than you owe, and a negative net worth means the opposite. Many young adults start their financial lives with a negative net worth, which is completely normal. A recent college graduate with $35,000 in student loans, a $500 checking account balance, and a $3,000 used car has a net worth of negative $31,500. That sounds alarming in isolation, but it is actually a typical starting point, and it improves rapidly once that person starts working, paying down debt, and building savings. The trajectory matters far more than any single snapshot, which is why tracking your net worth over time is one of the most powerful financial habits you can develop.</p>

        <h2 id="net-worth-vs-income">Why Net Worth Matters More Than Income</h2>
        <p>American culture tends to equate financial success with income, but some of the most financially precarious people in the country earn six-figure salaries. A household earning $200,000 per year with $500,000 in mortgage debt, $80,000 in car loans, $40,000 in student loans, and $15,000 in credit card balances might have a net worth that is barely positive despite their impressive income. Meanwhile, a school teacher earning $55,000 per year who has lived modestly for two decades, paid off their home, maxed out their <a href="/401k-calculator/">401(k)</a> each year, and avoided consumer debt might have a net worth well above $500,000. Income creates the potential for wealth, but only savings and asset accumulation turn that potential into reality.</p>
        <p>Thomas Stanley and William Danko documented this phenomenon extensively in their research on American millionaires. They found that the majority of people with a net worth exceeding one million dollars did not earn exceptionally high incomes. Instead, they were consistent savers who lived well below their means, avoided high-interest debt, invested steadily over decades, and let compound growth do the heavy lifting. The formula is not complicated, but it requires discipline and a long time horizon. Your <a href="/take-home-pay-calculator/">take-home pay</a> determines the raw material you have to work with, but your savings rate and investment choices determine how much of that material actually gets converted into lasting wealth.</p>

        <h2 id="components-of-net-worth">The Components of Net Worth: Assets and Liabilities</h2>
        <p>Your assets fall into several broad categories, each with different characteristics in terms of liquidity, growth potential, and risk. Cash and cash equivalents include your checking and savings accounts, money market funds, and certificates of deposit. These are the most liquid assets, meaning they can be converted to spendable cash within hours or days, but they also offer the lowest long-term growth potential. Investment accounts include your 401(k), traditional IRA, <a href="/roth-ira-calculator/">Roth IRA</a>, brokerage accounts, and any other securities you hold. These assets have higher growth potential over time but fluctuate in value with market conditions and may carry penalties for early withdrawal in the case of retirement accounts.</p>
        <p>Real estate represents another major asset category, typically in the form of your primary residence but also including rental properties or land. The equity you have in real estate is the current market value minus any outstanding mortgage balance. Vehicles, while technically assets, depreciate rapidly and are generally not considered wealth-building tools. Other assets might include business ownership interests, valuable personal property, cash value life insurance policies, and intellectual property. When calculating your net worth, include everything of meaningful value but be conservative with estimates. It is better to slightly understate your asset values than to inflate them and get a false sense of security.</p>
        <p>On the liability side, your debts are categorized by interest rate and purpose. Mortgage debt is generally considered productive debt because it finances an appreciating asset and typically carries a relatively low interest rate. Student loan debt occupies a middle ground, financing higher earning potential but sometimes at rates that make it a burden. Auto loans, personal loans, and credit card balances represent consumer debt, which is almost always counterproductive to wealth building. Credit card debt is particularly destructive because interest rates of 20 to 30 percent compound against you with the same mathematical force that compound growth uses to build your investments. Paying off high-interest debt is one of the most reliable ways to improve your net worth quickly, which is why tools like our <a href="/credit-card-payoff-calculator/">credit card payoff calculator</a> are so useful for planning a debt elimination strategy.</p>

        <h2 id="average-net-worth-by-age">Average and Median Net Worth by Age in America</h2>
        <p>The Federal Reserve's Survey of Consumer Finances, conducted every three years, provides the most authoritative data on American household wealth. The most recent survey shows dramatic variation in net worth both across age groups and within them. For households headed by someone under 35, the median net worth is approximately $39,000 while the mean is around $183,000. That massive gap between median and mean tells you that a small number of very wealthy young adults are pulling the average far above what a typical person in that age group actually has. The median is almost always the more useful comparison point for gauging where you stand relative to your peers.</p>
        <p>For the 35 to 44 age group, median net worth jumps to approximately $135,600, reflecting the accumulation that happens as careers advance and homeownership becomes more common. The 45 to 54 age group reaches a median of about $247,200, and the 55 to 64 group hits $364,500 as peak earning years and decades of investment growth push balances higher. Net worth typically peaks in the 65 to 74 age group at a median of roughly $409,900, then declines slightly for those 75 and older as retirees draw down their savings. If you find yourself well below the median for your age group, that is not a reason for despair but rather a signal that there are specific areas of your financial life worth examining more closely, whether that means increasing your savings rate, reducing debt, or adjusting your investment strategy.</p>

        <h2 id="growing-net-worth">How to Grow Your Net Worth Systematically</h2>
        <p>Net worth grows through three mechanisms, and the most successful wealth builders focus on all three simultaneously. The first mechanism is increasing the gap between your income and your spending. Every dollar you save is a dollar added to the asset side of the equation. You can widen this gap from either direction, by earning more through career advancement, side income, or negotiating raises, or by spending less through intentional budgeting and lifestyle choices. Use our <a href="/salary-calculator/">salary calculator</a> to understand your total compensation and identify opportunities to increase the income side of the equation.</p>
        <p>The second mechanism is reducing liabilities, particularly high-interest debt. Every dollar of credit card debt you eliminate improves your net worth by that same dollar, plus you stop the bleeding of interest payments that would have further eroded your financial position. Prioritize debts by interest rate, paying off the most expensive debt first while maintaining minimum payments on everything else. The third mechanism is asset appreciation, which happens when the value of your investments, real estate, or other holdings increases over time. This is where compound growth becomes your most powerful ally. An investment portfolio growing at 7 percent annually after inflation doubles approximately every ten years. A $50,000 portfolio at age 30 becomes $100,000 by 40, $200,000 by 50, and $400,000 by 60, assuming no additional contributions. With continued contributions, the numbers become even more impressive.</p>

        <h2 id="home-equity-role">The Role of Home Equity in Net Worth</h2>
        <p>For many American households, home equity represents the single largest component of their net worth. This is particularly true for middle-class families who may not have substantial investment portfolios but have been paying down a mortgage for ten or twenty years while their property appreciated in value. According to the Federal Reserve data, the median homeowner has a net worth roughly 40 times greater than the median renter, a gap that reflects both the forced savings mechanism of mortgage payments and the long-term appreciation of residential real estate.</p>
        <p>However, an overreliance on home equity carries risks that are worth understanding. Your home is an illiquid asset, meaning you cannot easily convert it to cash without selling it or taking on additional debt through a home equity loan or reverse mortgage. During housing market downturns, home values can decline significantly, as millions of Americans learned during the 2008 financial crisis. A diversified net worth that includes cash reserves, retirement accounts, taxable investment accounts, and real estate equity is far more resilient than one concentrated in a single asset class. Financial planners generally suggest that your primary residence should represent no more than 30 to 40 percent of your total net worth, though this percentage naturally varies by age and location. Our <a href="/mortgage-calculator/">mortgage calculator</a> and <a href="/rent-vs-buy-calculator/">rent vs. buy calculator</a> can help you think through the housing decisions that impact this balance.</p>

        <h2 id="tracking-net-worth">Tracking Net Worth Over Time as a Financial Health Metric</h2>
        <p>The real power of net worth as a financial metric comes not from any single calculation but from tracking it consistently over time. A quarterly or monthly net worth update gives you a trend line that reveals whether your financial life is moving in the right direction, and the act of reviewing the numbers regularly keeps your financial priorities front of mind. When your net worth is increasing quarter over quarter, you have tangible evidence that your savings habits, debt repayment, and investment strategy are working. When it stalls or declines for reasons other than a market correction, that is an early warning sign that something needs to change.</p>
        <p>Many people find that simply tracking their net worth changes their behavior without any additional effort. The awareness created by seeing the number go up after a month of disciplined saving, or watching it stagnate after a month of overspending, creates a feedback loop that reinforces good financial habits. It is similar to the well-documented effect that weighing yourself daily has on weight management. The measurement itself becomes a motivational tool. Set a calendar reminder to update your net worth on the first day of each quarter. Record the number in a spreadsheet along with the date and a brief note about any major financial events that occurred during the period, such as a bonus, a large purchase, or a debt payoff. Over the course of a year, you will have a clear picture of your financial trajectory that no budget app or account balance can match. Pair this practice with our <a href="/compound-interest-calculator/">compound interest calculator</a> to project where your investment accounts will be in five, ten, or twenty years based on your current trajectory, and use the <a href="/savings-calculator/">savings calculator</a> to set specific targets for the cash reserves and goal-based savings that contribute to your growing net worth.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>
</CalculatorLayout>
